    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Harsh Detention</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel Millstone letter, commenting on August 23 editorial supporting bail for Los Alamos weapons scientist Wen Ho Lee, scores harshness of Lee's pretrial detention</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your Aug. 23 editorial supporting bail for the Los Alamos weapons scientist Wen Ho Lee, you mention the harshness of his pretrial detention.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your Aug. 23 editorial supporting bail for the Los Alamos weapons scientist Wen Ho Lee, you mention the harshness of his pretrial detention.</p>
        <p>Both Amnesty International and the New York Academy of Sciences have expressed concerns about reports that Dr. Lee has been kept in solitary confinement 23 hours a day, has been shackled at his wrists and feet while being transported inside prison and during meetings with his family, and has had his feet restrained at meetings with his lawyers and in court.</p>
        <p>None of these measures are reasonably related to ensuring his attendance at trial or preventing him from spreading secrets.</p>
        <p>The government's coercive confinement of Dr. Lee amounts to pretrial punishment and should end even if bail is again denied.</p>
        <p>DANIEL MILLSTONE  Bronx, Aug. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
